es#37: Perform size, type, and permission validation after opening using fstat or an equivalent API."]\n["Rules#38: Avoid following symlinks or reparse points. Use flags or APIs that prevent following them."]\n["Rules#39: For outputs, set restrictive permissions at creation and never widen them later."]\n["Rules#40: Do not rely on per-file locks to prevent TOCTOU across processes. The primary control is open-then-validate-then-use on the same handle."]\n["Rules#41: When updating files, write to a temporary file, fsync, and perform an atomic rename or replacement within the same directory."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- POSIX: anchor file operations to a trusted directory using openat rather than absolute paths.\n- POSIX reads: openat(dirfd, rel, O_RDONLY | O_CLOEXEC | O_NOFOLLOW).\n- POSIX writes: openat(dirfd, rel, O_CREAT | O_EXCL | O_NOFOLLOW, 0600).\n- Immediately call fstat(fd) and reject if not a regular file or if size exceeds policy limits.\n- If stdio is needed, wrap the descriptor with fdopen(fd, mode) instead of reopening by path.\n- For safe writes on POSIX: create a temp file in the same directory, write, fflush and fsync the file, fsync the directory, then renameat or linkat plus unlink for an atomic move.\n- Windows: use CreateFileW with OPEN_EXISTING for reads or CREATE_NEW for writes, and FILE_FLAG_OPEN_REPARSE_POINT to avoid following reparse points. Validate with GetFileInformationByHandleEx and operate on the handle only. For atomic replacement, write to a temp file and call ReplaceFileW or MoveFileEx with MOVEFILE_WRITE_THROUGH.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- No check-then-use logic; file or resource is opened first, then validated\n- Code uses APIs that prevent following symlinks or reparse points\n- Validation occurs on opened handles using fstat or an equivalent API\n- Type and size checks are enforced after opening, not before\n- Writes use temporary files, fsync, and atomic renames or replacements\n- Permissions set restrictively on creation; not widened later\n- No reopening by path after validation; operations use the same descriptor or handle\n- Locks are not used as the sole protection against TOCTOU\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Avoid TOCTOU by removing check-before-open logic.\nInput:\n```\n/* Noncompliant: checks existence before open */\nFILE *fopen_if_not_exists(const char *file) {\n  if (access(file, F_OK) == -1 && errno == ENOENT) {\n    FILE *f = fopen(file, "w"); // Noncompliant\n    return f;\n  }\n  return NULL;\n}\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\n/* Compliant: open atomically with exclusive creation */\nFILE *fopen_if_not_exists(const char *file) {\n  FILE *f = fopen(file, "wx");\n  return f;\n}\n```\n### Example 2 (c)\nInstruction: Read a file safely with open-then-validate on POSIX.\nInput:\n```\n/* Noncompliant: stat then reopen by path */\nint read_conf(const char *path) {\n  struct stat st;\n  if (stat(path, &st) == 0 && S_ISREG(st.st_mode)) {\n    FILE *f = fopen(path, "rb");\n    if (!f) return -1;\n    /* ... */\n    fclose(f);\n    return 0;\n  }\n  return -1;\n}\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\n/* Compliant: open first, then validate, then use */\nint read_conf_at(int dirfd, const char *rel) {\n  int fd = openat(dirfd, rel, O_RDONLY | O_CLOEXEC | O_NOFOLLOW);\n  if (fd < 0) return -1;\n  struct stat st;\n  if (fstat(fd, &st) != 0 || !S_ISREG(st.st_mode) || st.st_size > MAX_SIZE) {\n    close(fd);\n    return -1;\n  }\n  FILE *f = fdopen(fd, "rb");\n  if (!f) { close(fd); return -1; }\n  /* read safely */\n  fclose(f);\n  return 0;\n}\n```\n### Example 3 (c)\nInstruction: Open and validate a file handle safely on Windows using C with WinAPI.\nInput:\n```\n// Noncompliant: GetFileAttributes then CreateFile by path later\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\n// Compliant: open and validate handle directly\nHANDLE h = CreateFileW(path, GENERIC_READ, FILE_SHARE_READ, NULL, OPEN_EXISTING,\n                       FILE_FLAG_OPEN_REPARSE_POINT | FILE_ATTRIBUTE_NORMAL, NULL);\nif (h == INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE) { /* handle error */ }\nFILE_STANDARD_INFO info;\nif (!GetFileInformationByHandleEx(h, FileStandardInfo, &info, sizeof(info)) || info.Directory) {\n    CloseHandle(h);\n}\n/* Use handle safely */\nCloseHandle(h);\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#43: Validate and sanitize every external input before use. Enforce expected type, format, encoding, length, and range."]\n["Rules#44: Use allow lists over block lists. Reject on validation failure and return minimal, generic error messages."]\n["Rules#45: Normalize and canonicalize paths, URLs, and identifiers before validation to prevent bypasses."]\n["Rules#46: Separate validation from business logic; run validation as early as possible at trust boundaries."]\n["Rules#47: Treat all input as untrusted, including environment variables, headers, cookies, query parameters, and file names."]\n["Rules#48: For structured data (JSON, XML, YAML), use strict schemas. Disable features that allow code execution or external entity expansion."]\n["Rules#49: Never hard code secrets. Read them from external configuration or a secret manager."]\n["Rules#50: Use constant format strings for logging. Do not log raw user input without redaction."]\n["Rules#51: For database access, use parameterized queries or safe ORM APIs. Never concatenate untrusted input into queries."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check buffer sizes before parsing or copying input. Validate numeric conversions and detect overflow.\n- Use strtol, strtoul, or strtod with end pointer checks. Reject on trailing junk or range errors.\n- For text input, bound reads with fgets and parse with length limits. Avoid scanf without width specifiers.\n- Normalize paths and reject traversal after normalization.\n- Use constant format strings with printf-family functions; never pass user input as a format string.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All inputs validated for type, format, encoding, length, and range\n- Strict schemas used for structured data; unsafe features disabled\n- No string concatenation used to build queries or commands\n- Normalization done before validation for paths and URLs\n- Validation errors return generic messages; detailed info goes only to secure logs\n- Logging uses constant format strings; sensitive data redacted\n- Dangerous parsers and dynamic execution features are not used on untrusted input\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Parse an integer from a string safely.\nInput:\n```\nint n = atoi(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse strtol with end pointer and errno checks, verify range, reject trailing characters, and handle errors without undefined behavior.\n```\n\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified. Document why each security measure is necessary with inline comments\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by line to confirm there are no weaknesses.\n5. Secure code output: output the final corrected code only, inside the four code blocks.\n', 'temperature': 1}}
