/* Noncompliant: stat then reopen by path */\nint read_conf(const char *path) {\n  struct stat st;\n  if (stat(path, &st) == 0 && S_ISREG(st.st_mode)) {\n    FILE *f = fopen(path, "rb");\n    if (!f) return -1;\n    /* ... */\n    fclose(f);\n    return 0;\n  }\n  return -1;\n}\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\n/* Compliant: open first, then validate, then use */\nint read_conf_at(int dirfd, const char *rel) {\n  int fd = openat(dirfd, rel, O_RDONLY | O_CLOEXEC | O_NOFOLLOW);\n  if (fd < 0) return -1;\n  struct stat st;\n  if (fstat(fd, &st) != 0 || !S_ISREG(st.st_mode) || st.st_size > MAX_SIZE) {\n    close(fd);\n    return -1;\n  }\n  FILE *f = fdopen(fd, "rb");\n  if (!f) { close(fd); return -1; }\n  /* read safely */\n  fclose(f);\n  return 0;\n}\n```\n### Example 3 (c)\nInstruction: Open and validate a file handle safely on Windows using C with WinAPI.\nInput:\n```\n// Noncompliant: GetFileAttributes then CreateFile by path later\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\n// Compliant: open and validate handle directly\nHANDLE h = CreateFileW(path, GENERIC_READ, FILE_SHARE_READ, NULL, OPEN_EXISTING,\n                       FILE_FLAG_OPEN_REPARSE_POINT | FILE_ATTRIBUTE_NORMAL, NULL);\nif (h == INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE) { /* handle error */ }\nFILE_STANDARD_INFO info;\nif (!GetFileInformationByHandleEx(h, FileStandardInfo, &info, sizeof(info)) || info.Directory) {\n    CloseHandle(h);\n}\n/* Use handle safely */\nCloseHandle(h);\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#34: Validate and sanitize every external input before use. Enforce expected type, format, encoding, length, and range."]\n["Rules#35: Use allow lists over block lists. Reject on validation failure and return minimal, generic error messages."]\n["Rules#36: Normalize and canonicalize paths, URLs, and identifiers before validation to prevent bypasses."]\n["Rules#37: Separate validation from business logic; run validation as early as possible at trust boundaries."]\n["Rules#38: Treat all input as untrusted, including environment variables, headers, cookies, query parameters, and file names."]\n["Rules#39: For structured data (JSON, XML, YAML), use strict schemas. Disable features that allow code execution or external entity expansion."]\n["Rules#40: Never hard code secrets. Read them from external configuration or a secret manager."]\n["Rules#41: Use constant format strings for logging. Do not log raw user input without redaction."]\n["Rules#42: For database access, use parameterized queries or safe ORM APIs. Never concatenate untrusted input into queries."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check buffer sizes before parsing or copying input. Validate numeric conversions and detect overflow.\n- Use strtol, strtoul, or strtod with end pointer checks. Reject on trailing junk or range errors.\n- For text input, bound reads with fgets and parse with length limits. Avoid scanf without width specifiers.\n- Normalize paths and reject traversal after normalization.\n- Use constant format strings with printf-family functions; never pass user input as a format string.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All inputs validated for type, format, encoding, length, and range\n- Strict schemas used for structured data; unsafe features disabled\n- No string concatenation used to build queries or commands\n- Normalization done before validation for paths and URLs\n- Validation errors return generic messages; detailed info goes only to secure logs\n- Logging uses constant format strings; sensitive data redacted\n- Dangerous parsers and dynamic execution features are not used on untrusted input\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Parse an integer from a string safely.\nInput:\n```\nint n = atoi(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse strtol with end pointer and errno checks, verify range, reject trailing characters, and handle errors without undefined behavior.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#44: Perform explicit bounds checks before every read or write. Use size-aware APIs and track lengths separately from buffers."]\n["Rules#45: Validate all size calculations for integer overflow before allocation and before memcpy or similar operations."]\n["Rules#46: Initialize pointers and buffers. Ensure strings are null terminated where required by the API."]\n["Rules#47: Prefer safe library functions or wrappers that take buffer size and return explicit status codes."]\n["Rules#48: Grow buffers dynamically only up to a defined maximum. Refuse inputs that exceed limits to avoid excessive memory use."]\n["Rules#49: Use memory-safe abstractions where available. Avoid manual pointer arithmetic unless necessary and well reviewed."]\n["Rules#50: On failure, do not use partially initialized buffers. Clear sensitive data before free using a guaranteed zeroization API."]\n["Rules#51: When reading from streams (for example fread or memchr workflows), bound the read by the remaining buffer size and verify the returned count before use."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check all allocation results for NULL and compute sizes with overflow checks (for example size_t n; if (n > SIZE_MAX / elem_size) fail).\n- Use snprintf, strnlen, memcpy with checked lengths, and memmove when regions may overlap.\n- Use fgets with a bound for input. Avoid gets and scanf without widths.\n- Validate indices and pointer arithmetic against buffer length. Use openat and fstat when validating file descriptors rather than path strings.\n- After fread, verify the number of bytes read before processing; when using memchr, check results and remaining length.\n\n### Checklist\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All allocations checked for NULL\n- All copies and reads bounded by destination size\n- All strings explicitly null terminated where required\n- Integer overflow checks before size arithmetic and allocation\n- Each function return value checked\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- Sensitive data cleared before free\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All reads and writes guarded by explicit bounds checks\n- All size arithmetic protected against integer overflow\n- Length tracked separately from buffer capacity and validated\n- Safe, size-aware APIs used; dangerous functions avoided\n- Buffer growth capped by a defined maximum; oversize inputs rejected\n- All return values checked; partial reads handled correctly\n- Sensitive data wiped before free; no double frees\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Fix an overflow when copying input into a fixed-size buffer.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; strcpy(buf, input);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nCheck the length of input, refuse if it exceeds sizeof(buf) - 1, then use snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "%s", input) to copy safely and enforce null termination.\n```\n\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified. Document why each security measure is necessary with inline comments\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by line to confirm there are no weaknesses.\n5. Secure code output: output the final corrected code only, inside the four code blocks.\n', 'temperature': 1}}
