tput:\n```\nUse strtol with end pointer and errno checks, verify range, reject trailing characters, and handle errors without undefined behavior.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#44: Perform explicit bounds checks before every read or write. Use size-aware APIs and track lengths separately from buffers."]\n["Rules#45: Validate all size calculations for integer overflow before allocation and before memcpy or similar operations."]\n["Rules#46: Initialize pointers and buffers. Ensure strings are null terminated where required by the API."]\n["Rules#47: Prefer safe library functions or wrappers that take buffer size and return explicit status codes."]\n["Rules#48: Grow buffers dynamically only up to a defined maximum. Refuse inputs that exceed limits to avoid excessive memory use."]\n["Rules#49: Use memory-safe abstractions where available. Avoid manual pointer arithmetic unless necessary and well reviewed."]\n["Rules#50: On failure, do not use partially initialized buffers. Clear sensitive data before free using a guaranteed zeroization API."]\n["Rules#51: When reading from streams (for example fread or memchr workflows), bound the read by the remaining buffer size and verify the returned count before use."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check all allocation results for NULL and compute sizes with overflow checks (for example size_t n; if (n > SIZE_MAX / elem_size) fail).\n- Use snprintf, strnlen, memcpy with checked lengths, and memmove when regions may overlap.\n- Use fgets with a bound for input. Avoid gets and scanf without widths.\n- Validate indices and pointer arithmetic against buffer length. Use openat and fstat when validating file descriptors rather than path strings.\n- After fread, verify the number of bytes read before processing; when using memchr, check results and remaining length.\n\n### Checklist\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All allocations checked for NULL\n- All copies and reads bounded by destination 