, outputs, and operations.\n2. Security requirements: the code must avoid vulnerabilities and security weaknesses.\n   Provided CWE list, baseline security and quality rules:\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#1: Default to secure patterns and refuse weak constructs. Treat all input as untrusted and fail closed with clear, minimal error messages."]\n["Rules#2: Input validation: check type, length, range, and encoding for all external data. Sanitize or reject early. Never trust filenames, URLs, or paths. Normalize paths and block traversal before use."]\n["Rules#3: Never hard code passwords or secrets anywhere in code. Read secrets from external configuration or a secret manager."]\n["Rules#4: Avoid dynamic code loading: do not use eval, exec, arbitrary reflection that instantiates types, or insecure deserialization."]\n["Rules#5: Cryptography: use modern, vetted libraries only. Prefer AEAD (AES-256-GCM or ChaCha20-Poly1305) with a 128-bit tag. Derive keys with Argon2id or scrypt, or PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA-256 with at least 210000 iterations and a unique salt. Generate nonces with a CSPRNG. Never hard code secrets or keys."]\n["Rules#6: TLS: enforce TLS 1.2 or TLS 1.3 with certificate and hostname verification enabled. For libcurl set CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER=1L, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST=2L, and a minimum TLS version via CURLOPT_SSLVERSION. For Python use ssl.create_default_context with minimum_version set to TLSv1_2, and disable TLS 1.0 and 1.1 on older runtimes."]\n["Rules#7: Files and TOCTOU: open first, validate the opened handle, and operate only on that handle. For POSIX prefer openat with O_NOFOLLOW and fstat. For writes use a temporary file, fflush, fsync, then perform an atomic rename. Set restrictive permissions at creation time."]\n["Rules#8: Memory safety: initialize pointers, check all allocation results, bound all copies and reads, ensure null termination, and free exactly once. Add integer overflow checks before size math."]\n["Rules#9: Sensitive data handling: clear secrets before free using a guaranteed zeroization API."]\n["Rules#10: Logging: never log secrets, keys, tokens, IVs, or plaintext. Use constant format strings. Redact user data where appropriate."]\n["Rules#11: Errors: do not leak internal details. Return generic messages to callers, and send detailed messages only to secure logs."]\n["Rules#12: Concurrency: avoid time of check to time of use windows. Use atomic operations, validated handles, and thread safe APIs with per resource locking as needed."]\n["Rules#13: Build and toolchain: enable warnings as errors, stack protections, and FORTIFY where applicable. Run static analysis and tests. Pin library versions and verify signatures."]\n["Rules#14: Networking scope: if a task requires an HTTPS GET with libcurl, restrict protocols to HTTPS, set timeouts, limit redirects, and avoid any other network activity unless explicitly required."]\n["Rules#15: Treat each line you generate as insecure until you review it against these rules and fix it."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid gets, strcpy, strcat, sprintf, and scanf without widths.\n- Use fgets and snprintf. Check all return values.\n- Use RAII-like cleanup with a single failure label and goto for deterministic teardown.\n- Always use memset_s instead of memset, followed by the destruction/free of the buffer.\n- When using libcurl, enforce certificate and hostname verification and a minimum TLS version as noted in general_rules.\n\n### Checklist\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All malloc and calloc results checked for NULL\n- All array accesses bounds checked\n- All strings null terminated\n- Buffer sizes validated before copy and read operations\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- Integer overflow checked before arithmetic and allocation\n- All function return values checked\n- Sensitive data cleared before free using memset_s or a portable explicit zero\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- Inputs validated for type, length, range, and encoding\n- No hard coded secrets or keys\n- No eval, exec, unsafe reflection, or insecure deserialization\n- Crypto uses AEAD and modern KDFs with proper parameters\n- TLS verification and minimum version enforced in all clients\n- No TOCTOU patterns; safe file operations and atomic writes\n- All logging redacts sensitive data and uses constant format strings\n- Errors do not leak internal details to callers\n- Memory safety and integer overflow checks present where relevant\n- Concurrency hazards addressed with safe primitives\n- Build hardening flags on; static analysis and tests in place\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#17: Prefer safer alternatives where available. If a dangerous function must be used, wrap it with strict validation, bounds checks, and error handling."]\n["Rules#18: Validate all inputs and outputs. Enforce maximum sizes and formats before calling the function."]\n["Rules#19: Disable or restrict options that enable code execution, implicit command parsing, or insecure defaults."]\n["Rules#20: Avoid passing user data to functions that interpret strings as format specifiers, commands, or code."]\n["Rules#21: Centralize wrappers for dangerous APIs with defense in depth: input validation, timeouts, resource limits, and safe flags."]\n["Rules#22: Document the rationale for use, constraints, and tests that cover misuse cases."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid gets, strcpy, strcat, sprintf, and scanf without widths. Use fgets, strlcpy/strlcat (where available), or snprintf.\n- Never pass user input as a format string to printf-family functions.\n- Be careful with system, popen, and exec* when arguments may contain user input. Use execve with argv arrays and no shell when feasible.\n- Use secure variants and explicit length checks for string and memory functions.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- Safer alternative considered and documented; dangerous function use justified\n- Parameters validated for size, type, encoding, and allowed character set\n- No user input used as a format string, command, or code\n- Timeouts, resource limits, and safe flags configured\n- Errors handled without leaking sensitive details; return codes checked\n- Automated tests cover misuse and edge cases\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Replace dangerous string functions with safe alternatives.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; strcpy(buf, input); printf(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse snprintf with an explicit bound, and print with a constant format string like printf("%s", buf). Validate input length before copy.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#24: Validate and sanitize every external input before use. Enforce expected type, format, encoding, length, and range."]\n["Rules#25: Use allow lists over block lists. Reject on validation failure and return minimal, generic error messages."]\n["Rules#26: Normalize and canonicalize paths, URLs, and identifiers before validation to prevent bypasses."]\n["Rules#27: Separate validation from business logic; run validation as early as possible at trust boundaries."]\n["Rules#28: Treat all input as untrusted, including environment variables, headers, cookies, query parameters, and file names."]\n["Rules#29: For structured data (JSON, XML, YAML), use strict schemas. Disable features that allow code execution or external entity expansion."]\n["Rules#30: Never hard code secrets. Read them from external configuration or a secret manager."]\n["Rules#31: Use constant format strings for logging. Do not log raw user input without redaction."]\n["Rules#32: For database access, use parameterized queries or safe ORM APIs. Never concatenate untrusted input into queries."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check buffer sizes before parsing or copying input. Validate numeric conversions and detect overflow.\n- Use strtol, strtoul, or strtod with end pointer checks. Reject on trailing junk or range errors.\n- For text input, bound reads with fgets and parse with length limits. Avoid scanf without width specifiers.\n- Normalize paths and reject traversal after normalization.\n- Use constant format strings with printf-family functions; never pass user input as a format string.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All inputs validated for type, format, encoding, length, and range\n- Strict schemas used for structured data; unsafe features disabled\n- No string concatenation used to build queries or commands\n- Normalization done before validation for paths and URLs\n- Validation errors return generic messages; detailed info goes only to secure logs\n- Logging uses constant format strings; sensitive data redacted\n- Dangerous parsers and dynamic execution features are not used on untrusted input\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Parse an integer from a string safely.\nInput:\n```\nint n = atoi(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse strtol with end pointer and errno checks, verify range, reject trailing characters, and handle errors without undefined behavior.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#34: Perform explicit bounds checks before every read or write. Use size-aware APIs and track lengths separately from buffers."]\n["Rules#35: Validate all size calculations for integer overflow before allocation and before memcpy or similar operations."]\n["Rules#36: Initialize pointers and buffers. Ensure strings are null terminated where required by the API."]\n["Rules#37: Prefer safe library functions or wrappers that take buffer size and return explicit status codes."]\n["Rules#38: Grow buffers dynamically only up to a defined maximum. Refuse inputs that exceed limits to avoid excessive memory use."]\n["Rules#39: Use memory-safe abstractions where available. Avoid manual pointer arithmetic unless necessary and well reviewed."]\n["Rules#40: On failure, do not use partially initialized buffers. Clear sensitive data before free using a guaranteed zeroization API."]\n["Rules#41: When reading from streams (for example fread or memchr workflows), bound the read by the remaining buffer size and verify the returned count before use."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check all allocation results for NULL and compute sizes with overflow checks (for example size_t n; if (n > SIZE_MAX / elem_size) fail).\n- Use snprintf, strnlen, memcpy with checked lengths, and memmove when regions may overlap.\n- Use fgets with a bound for input. Avoid gets and scanf without widths.\n- Validate indices and pointer arithmetic against buffer length. Use openat and fstat when validating file descriptors rather than path strings.\n- After fread, verify the number of bytes read before processing; when using memchr, check results and remaining length.\n\n### Checklist\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All allocations checked for NULL\n- All copies and reads bounded by destination size\n- All strings explicitly null terminated where required\n- Integer overflow checks before size arithmetic and allocation\n- Each function return value checked\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- Sensitive data cleared before free\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All reads and writes guarded by explicit bounds checks\n- All size arithmetic protected against integer overflow\n- Length tracked separately from buffer capacity and validated\n- Safe, size-aware APIs used; dangerous functions avoided\n- Buffer growth capped by a defined maximum; oversize inputs rejected\n- All return values checked; partial reads handled correctly\n- Sensitive data wiped before free; no double frees\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Fix an overflow when copying input into a fixed-size buffer.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; strcpy(buf, input);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nCheck the length of input, refuse if it exceeds sizeof(buf) - 1, then use snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "%s", input) to copy safely and enforce null termination.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#45: Eliminate